==Latin==

===Etymology===
Back-formed from the accusative {{term/t|la|diem}}, at a time when the vowel was still long. From {{etyl|itc-pro|la}} {{term/t|itc-pro|*djēm}}, the accusative of {{term/t|itc-pro|*djous}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*dyew-||heaven, sky; to shine}}. The Italic stem was also the source of {{term/t|la|Iovis}}, the genitive of {{term/t|la|Iuppiter}}, and was generally interchangeable with it in earlier times (still shown by the analogical formation {{term/t|la|Diēspiter}}). The original nominative survives as {{term/t|la||*diūs}} in two fossilised phrases: {{term/t|la|mediusfidius|mē diūs fidius|pos=an interjection}} and {{term/t|la|nudiustertius|nū diūs tertius|day before yesterday|lit=now (is) the third day}}.

Cognate with Old Armenian {{term|տիւ||daytime|sc=Armn|tr=tiw|lang=xcl}}, Old Irish {{term|día|lang=sga}}, Welsh {{term|dydd|lang=cy}}. English {{term|day|lang=en}} is a false cognate (see there).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈdɪ.eːs/|lang=la}}

===Noun===
{{la-noun|diēs||diēī|m|g2=f|fifth}}

# [[day]] {{gloss|any period of twenty-four hours}}
# day {{gloss|part of a day period between sunrise and sunset where one enjoys daylight}}
# {{context|often in the feminine|lang=la}} a set day or [[appointed]] time; [[date]], [[appointment]]

====Inflection====
''Diēs'' is an exceptional case of a fifth declension noun since it is both used in the masculine form and in the feminine form, instead of just feminine like the rest of the fifth declension nouns. The masculine use is more common, and almost invariable in the plural. The feminine use is found in the singular when the day is being personified as a goddess, when it refers to a specific day (e.g., the date of a letter, or an appointed day for business), when it refers to the passing of time, and occasionally in other contexts.

